# AFK blocker log — Kue slice loop

## B3d-4 live-registry fetch — BLOCKER (needs a human; logged, not failed)

- **What:** B3d-4 (OCI fetch over a curl subprocess) is implemented and offline-verified.
  The pure URL/argv/Accept builders (`Kue/Oci.lean`) are `native_decide`-pinned, and the
  impure edge (`Kue/OciFetch.lean`: `runCurl`/`curlGet`/`curlGetVerified`/`fetchManifest`/
  `fetchBlob`/`fetchModuleZip`) is driven end-to-end through `curl` against `file://`
  fixtures by `scripts/check-ocifetch.lean` (wired into `scripts/check-fixtures.sh`),
  including the digest-mismatch REJECTION path. What was NOT run: a real HTTPS GET from
  `registry.cue.works`.

- **Why it needs a human:** the only true verification of the live edge is an actual
  network egress to a real registry, which is OUTSIDE the AFK envelope (no outward-facing
  / network actions, no writes outside the tree). So the live smoke is human-gated, not
  auto-run.

- **What to run to verify (one-liner, no Kue needed — exercises the exact request shape
  B3d-4 builds):** fetch a real CUE module manifest from the Central Registry. Pick a
  module known to be published, e.g. the registry's own probe, and GET its manifest with
  the same flags + Accept headers Kue emits:

      curl -sSL --fail-with-body \
        -H "Accept: application/vnd.oci.image.manifest.v1+json" \
        -H "Accept: application/vnd.oci.image.index.v1+json" \
        -H "Accept: */*" \
        https://registry.cue.works/v2/<module-path>/manifests/<version>

  (Replace `<module-path>`/`<version>` with a real published module, e.g. one of your own
  `prodigy9.co/...@v...` deps. A 2xx + a JSON manifest body confirms the live path; the
  config `mediaType` should be `application/vnd.cue.module.v1+json`.) Then GET the zip
  blob it references:

      curl -sSL --fail-with-body \
        https://registry.cue.works/v2/<module-path>/blobs/<zip-layer-digest>

  Once B3d-5 wires the edge into the resolver, the integration smoke becomes: delete the
  dep from vendor + cache, then `kue export <file>` and confirm it fetches + digest-verifies
  + resolves (instead of the `registry fetch is B3d` error). A one-word go-ahead unblocks
  running the live smoke.

- **Note (auth):** `registry.cue.works` serves public modules anonymously, so the GET above
  needs no token. Authenticated/private registries (Bearer-token `WWW-Authenticate` flow)
  are a deferred B3d-6 concern — see `docs/spec/compat-assumptions.md`.

## B3d-5 live-registry fetch-on-missing — BLOCKER (needs a human; logged, not failed)

- **What:** B3d-5 (fetch→extract→cache-write→read-path wiring) is implemented and
  OFFLINE-verified. `Kue.fetchAndCacheModule` resolves a declared-but-missing dep's
  `CUE_REGISTRY`+modpath@ver to an `OciRef`, fetches the digest-verified zip
  (`OciFetch.fetchModuleZip`), unzips+CRC-verifies (`Zip.readZip`), optionally checks a
  `cue.sum` `h1:`, writes the raw zip + extracted entries into the cue cache
  (`mod/download/...` + `mod/extract/...`), and retries `locateModuleDir`. Driven end-to-end
  by `scripts/check-fetch-pipeline.lean` (wired into `scripts/check-fixtures.sh`) against a
  local fixture zip with `CUE_CACHE_DIR` pointed at a repo-local temp dir — install, locate,
  download-layout, cue.sum accept/reject, `none`-registry, and transport-failure paths all
  pinned. What was NOT run (out of AFK envelope): a real HTTPS fetch of a genuinely-missing
  dep from `registry.cue.works` (network egress + a WRITE to the real `~/Library/Caches/cue`).

- **Why a human:** the live path makes an outbound HTTPS request to the Central Registry AND
  writes into the real user cache — both outside the AFK no-network / no-out-of-tree-writes
  envelope.

- **Exact human smoke (one run unblocks it):**
  1. Pick a real dep already declared in `prod9/infra` (`prodigy9.co/defs@v0` at `v0.3.19`).
  2. Remove it from BOTH the vendor tree and the real cache so kue MUST fetch:
     `rm -rf ~/Library/Caches/cue/mod/extract/prodigy9.co ~/Library/Caches/cue/mod/download/prodigy9.co`
     (and ensure `cue.mod/pkg/prodigy9.co` is absent — it already is on this checkout).
  3. From `/Users/chakrit/Documents/prod9/infra`, run
     `/Users/chakrit/Documents/chakrit/kue/.lake/build/bin/kue export --out json apps/argocd.cue`.
  4. EXPECT: a successful fetch+digest-verify+extract+load — the export matches `cue export`
     (`diff <(kue …|jq -S .) <(cue …|jq -S .)` = 0 lines) — instead of the old
     `… not found in vendor or cue cache … registry fetch is B3d` error. Confirm the module
     reappeared at `~/Library/Caches/cue/mod/extract/prodigy9.co/defs@v0.3.19/`.

- **Note (cue.sum):** cue v0.16.1 ships NO `cue.sum` file mechanism (no `HashZip`/dirhash
  consumer in its source) — the OCI blob `sha256:` digest (already gated in `fetchBlob`) is
  the live integrity check. kue's `cue.sum` `h1:` verification is defensive/forward-compatible
  (enforced when a `cue.sum` is present, skipped when absent). Recorded in
  `docs/reference/cue-spec-gaps.md`. WRITING/maintaining `cue.sum` (`cue mod tidy`) stays
  B3d-6.

- **Note (auth):** as B3d-4 — `registry.cue.works` serves public modules anonymously, no
  token needed; private/Bearer-token registries are B3d-6.

